conjecture(fta): every non-constant complex polynomial has a root

The fundamental theorem of algebra: a polynomial of degree at least one with
complex coefficients has a root in the complex numbers.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(dalembert): an analytic argument via local power series

Jean d'Alembert argues that the modulus of a polynomial, if never zero, could
always be decreased, so it must reach zero somewhere.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:fta
---
refute(dalembert)!: the argument rests on unproven analytic facts

The step that the modulus can always be decreased relies on convergence and
continuity results not available, and not established, at the time.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: dalembert
BREAKING CHANGE: d'Alembert's proof is incomplete; the theorem is unproven again.
---
proof(gauss-1799): a geometric proof from Gauss's dissertation

Gauss argues that two real algebraic curves, the real and imaginary parts of the
polynomial, must intersect.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:fta
---
refute(gauss-1799)!: the curves are assumed to meet without proof

The crossing of the two curves is taken as geometrically obvious. A rigorous
topological justification is supplied only by Ostrowski in 1920.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: gauss-1799
BREAKING CHANGE: Gauss's first proof has a topological gap.
---
proof(argand): the minimum-modulus proof

Jean-Robert Argand shows the modulus of a polynomial attains a minimum, and that
a non-zero minimum could be lowered, so the minimum is zero.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:fta
---
proof(gauss-rigorous): Gauss's later, complete proofs

Gauss returns with proofs that avoid the earlier gap, including a largely
algebraic argument.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:fta
Supersedes: gauss-1799
---
proof(galois-algebraic): an algebraic proof using real-closed fields

From only two analytic facts, that odd-degree real polynomials have a root and
that positive reals have square roots, a Galois-theoretic argument finishes the
rest purely algebraically.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:fta
---
formalize(fta): a kernel-checked proof in Coq

The FTA project formalises the analytic proof in Coq, so the theorem is checked
by the kernel end to end.

Formal-Statement: rocq:FTA.fundamental_theorem_of_algebra
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: Coq
Closes: conjecture:fta
Cites: Geuvers et al. 2000
